{% block content %}
  <h2>Scams and online safety</h2>
  <p>Common scams target Elders by phone, text, email, and social media: fake calls from a bank or government, the grandparent scam, romance scams, and demands for payment in gift cards, crypto, or wire transfers. The plain rules: never share your SIN, banking details, passwords, or codes; no real government agency demands gift cards, crypto, or a wire transfer; and talk to a trusted person before sending money to anyone. Report fraud to the Canadian Anti-Fraud Centre at 1-888-495-8501.</p>

  <h2>Elder abuse</h2>
  <p>Elder abuse can be financial, physical, emotional, or neglect, often by someone in a position of trust. If you see the signs, you can reach out. Elder Abuse Prevention Ontario offers fact sheets and a seniors safety line, and the family-safety supports in this section can help. If an Elder is in immediate danger, call 911.</p>

